      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, can u explain what a durable power of attorney is? i'm trying to help my dad with some estate stuff and i'm a bit confused about how it differs from just a regular power of attorney.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A durable power of attorney is a legal document that grants your dad the power to act on your behalf, but with a crucial difference: it remains valid even if he loses his mental capacity or becomes incapacitated. In contrast, a regular power of attorney usually expires once the principal (your dad) loses the ability to make decisions, which is why it's often called \"non-durable.\"\n\nThink of a regular power of attorney like a temporary job contract that ends when the boss gets sick or quits. If your dad's health declines, that contract dissolves, and you might be left holding the bag without a clear legal path to manage his affairs. A durable power of attorney, however, is like a contract that says, \"I will keep working even if you can't walk or speak,\" ensuring that your dad's assets and daily life continue to be managed smoothly by someone you trust.\n\nIt's like hiring a reliable butler who stays in the house even if the master falls ill; the butler's job doesn't end because the master can't move. Without this specific type of document, you'd have to scramble to find a new person to manage his estate, which could be a nightmare.\n\nSo, to summarize: a",
      "source": "target",
